description: From Latin connatus. Doublet of cognate.

adjectives.description: connate (comparative more connate, superlative most connate)

entries.meaning: Of the same or a similar nature; proceeding from the same stock or root.
examples: Synonyms: akin, cognate; see also Thesaurus:akin

entries.meaning: (botany) United with other organs of the same kind (for example sepals connate with sepals, petals connate with petals, or stamens with stamens).
(geology) Trapped within a rock at the time of its formation (especially of water or petroleum).
